com.samysadi.acs.utility.collections

Class AbstractMultiListView<E>

  • java.lang.Object
    • java.util.AbstractCollection<E>
      • com.samysadi.acs.utility.collections.AbstractMultiListView<E>
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Iterable<E>, Collection<E>, List<E>, RandomAccess
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    MultiListView

    public abstract class AbstractMultiListView<E>
extends AbstractCollection<E>
implements List<E>, RandomAccess
    A list that gives a "read-only" view of multiple lists so that they appear as one unique merged list without them being actually merged.
    This list does not contain a merged copy of each of the underlying lists. So, this has lesser memory usage, than creating a list and add all the underlying lists.

    Because this list is unmodifiable (read-only), all attempts to modify it, whether directly or via its iterator, result in an UnsupportedOperationException.

    You have to override the lists() and size() methods to use this list.
    The size() method must return an integer that is equal to the sum of the sizes of each of the lists returned by the lists() method.
    The list returned by the lists() method may safely contain null lists.

    Note This list is optimized to be used with RandomAccess lists. If lists() is not, or contains non-RandomAccess lists, then you will probably experience important performance issues.

    Since:
    1.0
